    <p class="paragraph">
        During WWI, Amelia Earhart served as a Red Cross nurse’s aid in Canada and watched pilots train. In 1921, she finally <br>
        started flying lessons with a female flight instructor by working extra jobs. She set records, such as becoming the first <br> 
        woman to fly solo above 14,000 ft, and, in 1932, she was the first woman to fly solo across the Atlantic Ocean. She won the <br>
        Distinguished Flying Cross for her “heroism” and made her first solo nonstop flight across the United States by a woman. <br>
        Throughout her life, she worked to promote opportunities for women in aviation and formed the Ninety-Nines, an advancement <br>
        of female pilots. She disappeared on a trip to Howland Island, however, her hard work and empowerment mark her a success.
    </p>
